questiontext.text:
Resolving one vector along another

The scalar product can be used to find the component of a vector in the direction of another vector. Consider the figure below which shows two arbitrary vectors \(\underline{a}\) and \(\underline{n}\). Let \(\underline{\hat{n}}\) be a unit vector in the direction of \(\underline{n}\).

Study the figure carefully and note that a perpendicular has been drawn from \(P\) to meet \(\underline{n}\) at \(Q\). The distance \(OQ\) is called the projection of \(\underline{a}\) onto \(\underline{n}\). Simple trigonometry tells us that the length of the projection is \(|\underline{a}|\cos\theta\). Now by taking the scalar product of \(\underline{a}\) with the unit vector \(\underline{\hat{n}}\) we find 


  \(\qquad\underline{a}\cdot\underline{\hat{n}} =|\underline{a}|\,|\hat{\underline{n}}|\,\cos\theta =|\underline{a}|\cos\theta\qquad\qquad\hbox{(since } |\underline{\hat{n}}|=1)\) 


 We conclude that

Key Point

\[\underline{a}\cdot \underline{\hat{n}} \hbox{ is the component of } \underline{a} \hbox{ in the direction of } \underline{n}\]

Example

The figure above shows a plane containing the point \(A\) which has position vector \(\underline{a}\). The vector \(\underline{\hat{n}}\) is a unit vector perpendicular to the plane (such a vector is called a unit normal vector). Find an expression for the perpendicular distance, \(\ell\), of the plane from the origin.


Solution

From the diagram we note that the perpendicular distance \(\ell\) of the plane from the origin is the projection of \(\underline{a}\) onto \(\underline{\hat{n}}\) and, using the previous Key point, is thus \(\underline{a}\cdot \hat{\underline{n}}\).
